<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>douglasii</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>prociduum</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>sphaerocephalum</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>strictum</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>umbellatum</i> and/or <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i> are characteristic of the alliance with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>arbuscula</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i> and/or <i>Purshia</i> <i>tridentata</i>. Associated herbs include <i>Blepharipappus</i> <i>scaber</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>tectorum</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i>, <i>Epilobium</i> <i>brachycarpum</i> and <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>vimineum</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 0.5 m; canopy is open. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent and/or grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li>Dwarf-shrub <i>Eriogonum</i> spp. (<i>E. sphaerocephalum</i>, <i>E. prociduum</i>, <i>E. umbellatum</i>) are characteristically present even as low as < 1% cover and usually no other shrubs are present with greater cover (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li>One or more <i>Eriogonum</i> dwarf-shrub species 2-40% cover with 10-60% herbaceous cover dominated by <i>Poa secunda</i> (NatureServe 2019).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> All slopes and exposures, but most common on southern slopes and flat to undulating ridgetops and plateaus. Soils are shallow with a high percentage of rock fragments and exposed rock. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Poa secunda</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
