<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> In California, this alliance is characterized by the presence of one or more <i>Eriogonum</i> dwarf-shrub species including <i>E. douglasii, E. prociduum, E. sphaerocephalum, E. strictum, </i>and/or <i>E. umbellatum</i>. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum douglasii</i> is a perennial mat-forming herb or subshrub usually under 60 cm tall. Leaves are densely tomentose. Inflorescenses are head-like with yellow to rose-red flowers (Jepson Flora Project 2020). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum prociduum</i> is a small (under 10 cm) mat-forming perennial. Leaves are silvery, tomentose and ovate to narrowly lanceolate. The erect inflorescence stalks bear rounded clusters of bright yellow flowers (Jepson Flora Project 2020). <i>E. prociduum</i> grows from the Modoc Plateau to northwestern Nevada and southern Oregon in clay and exposed volcanic soils. It has a CNPS rare plant rank of 1B.2. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum sphaerocephalum</i> is a small shrub or subshrub (approximately 50 cm tall and wide). Tomentose leaves grow in basal rosettes around a woody caudex. Flowers are borne in head-like clusters or umbels on bracted stalks. Two varieties are recognized based on flower size and color: var. <i>halimioides</i> has pale yellow to cream flowers while var. <i>sphaerocephalum</i> has bright yellow flowers. Both varieties are found in the Modoc Plateau and typically grow in sand or gravel (Jepson Flora Project 2020). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum strictum</i> is a perennial or subshrub. Leaves are generally tomentose. Inflorescence is umbel-like and flowers can be white or yellow to rose or purple (Jepson Flora Project 2020). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum umbellatum</i> is a perennial herb to subshrub. There are 25 variaties recognized in California and the varieties vary greatly by ecological settings and physical characteristics. The varieties found within this alliance are low growing subshrubs typically under 50 cm. Leaves can be tomentose or glabrous and infloresences are umbel-like. Flowers are white, yellow, or red (Jepson Flora Project 2020).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Poa secunda </i>is a native, cool-season, perennial bunchgrass that is shallowly rooted. It regenerates by tillers, by seed, and by facultatively apomictic seed. It is not shade tolerant. It produces little litter, and its small size along with its sparse litter reduces the amount of heat transferred to perennating buds in the soil (Howard 1997c). The species occurs throughout California, but the habitats of the two subspecies differ; ssp. <i>juncifolia </i> is associated with mesic flood plains and internally drained basins and is not covered by this alliance, whereas ssp. <i>secunda </i> grows on ridges, plateaus, and benches on steep canyon slopes (Soreng 2007). <br/>
<br/>
This alliance occurs on flats or exposed hilltops with significant volcanic cobble and/or gravel covering the soil surface. These xeric sites have shallow rocky soils with limited water-holding capacity. Winter precipitation wets the soil, but they typically dry out completely by mid-summer (Daubenmire 1970). <br/>
<br/>
The above species are characteristic of this alliance in California with <i>Eriogonum</i> spp. having as low as < 1% cover and usually no other shrubs are present with greater cover. Total vegetation cover is usually < 10% and often < 5% (VegCAMP 2020). The herbaceous layer is typically dominated by perennial bunchgrasses, with sparse to moderate cover of perennial forbs. Annual forbs and grasses may be seasonally abundant. Moss and lichen cover in undisturbed stands is often high (NatureServe 2019). <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is related to the <i>Artemisia arbuscula - Eriogonum (microthecum, sphaerocephalum)</i> Association (of the <i>Artemisia arbuscula</i> alliance), but occurs on harsher sites where an evenly-distributed shrub layer dominated by <i>Artemisia arbuscula</i> is unlikely (VegCAMP 2020). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
