    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The highest concentration of stands in this alliance occurs on lower slopes and foothills in the Modoc Plateau (Geographical Information Center, in progress). Smaller stands are scattered throughout northeastern California, and the probability of stands occurring in areas where they have not been observed is supported by records from Calflora and CCH.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gb-p). Many stands have been sampled throughout this section, and large stands have been mapped in the hills east of California Pines, near Ash Valley, and near Whitefinger Mountain.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Db, Dk). Stands occur around the edges of Slinkard Valley (Boul et al. 2021a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba-e). Stands occur on the middle to lower slopes of Shaffer Mountain, Five Springs Mountain, and Snowstorm Mountain.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-d, Ei-j, En). Stands have been sampled between the Diamond Mountains and Red Clover Valley as well as near Martis Creek Lake.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Dh, Dj). Stands are expected to occur in this section based on CCH and Calflora records.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands of <i>Eriogonum prociduum</i> are possibly threatened by trampling, grazing and non-native plant invasion (CNPS 2020). 

Stands of this alliance are generally considered to be late-seral with species composition controlled by the harsh edaphic conditions of the site. Disturbances such as grazing and trampling by livestock cause  increased erosion and bare ground with a decrease in moss cover (Daubenmire 1970). Frost heaving causes local soil disturbance when the thin, saturated soils freeze and push plants out of the ground in winter. 

Non-native plants have invaded many stands, especially stands that have already been disturbed. Common non-natives include annual grasses such as <i>Bromus arvensis</i> and <i>B. tectorum</i> and forbs such as <i>Erodium cicutarium, Lactuca serriola,</i> and <i>Tragopogon dubius</i>. Fire is not considered a common disturbance in these stands because it is unlikely that the sparse vegetation will carry fire (NatureServe 2019). </div>
</div>

    

    

